<h2>HVAC Systems in Idaho</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Idaho's diverse climate zones require careful consideration when selecting and installing HVAC systems. The state experiences a continental climate with cold winters and warm summers, though specific conditions vary significantly from the northern panhandle to the southern desert regions. Winter temperatures commonly drop below freezing across the state, with some areas experiencing prolonged periods well below zero, necessitating robust heating systems capable of maintaining comfort during extreme cold snaps.</p>

<p>Summer temperatures in southern Idaho frequently exceed 90¬∞F, with some areas reaching over 100¬∞F during heat waves, creating substantial cooling demands. The state's low humidity levels, typically ranging from 30-50%, provide natural evaporative cooling benefits but also present unique challenges for HVAC system sizing and operation. This dry climate allows for highly effective evaporative cooling systems in many areas, offering energy-efficient alternatives to traditional air conditioning.</p>

<p>The significant temperature swings between seasons, often exceeding 100¬∞F difference between winter lows and summer highs, require HVAC systems capable of efficient operation across a wide range of conditions. Heat pump technology has become increasingly popular in Idaho, particularly in moderate climate zones, as modern cold-climate heat pumps can operate effectively even in sub-zero temperatures while providing efficient cooling during hot summers.</p>

