<h2>Idaho Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Idaho offers several attractive incentives for solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems that significantly reduce the overall investment cost for residents and businesses. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, allowing Idaho homeowners to deduct 30% of their total solar system cost from their federal taxes. This substantial incentive applies to both residential and commercial installations and includes equipment, installation labor, and associated electrical work.</p>

<p>At the state level, Idaho provides a valuable property tax exemption for renewable energy systems, including solar panels and geothermal systems. This exemption ensures that adding solar panels to your property will not increase your property tax assessment, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime. The exemption applies to 100% of the added value from renewable energy installations, making it particularly beneficial for larger residential and commercial systems.</p>

<p>Idaho Power Company offers various energy efficiency programs and rebates for qualifying HVAC equipment and home energy improvements. The utility's Energy Efficiency Program provides rebates for high-efficiency heat pumps, air conditioning units, and ductless mini-split systems that meet specific efficiency criteria. Residential customers can receive rebates ranging from \$300 to \$1,500 for qualifying HVAC equipment, depending on the system type and efficiency rating. Additionally, Idaho Power offers free energy audits and weatherization rebates that can help optimize HVAC system performance and reduce overall energy consumption.</p>

<p>The utility also participates in net metering programs, allowing solar customers to receive credit for excess electricity generated by their systems and fed back into the grid. Idaho Power's net metering policy credits customers at the retail rate for excess generation during billing periods, providing additional value for solar installations. Low-income households may qualify for additional assistance through Idaho Power's Low Income Weatherization Program and the state's Weatherization Assistance Program, which provide free energy efficiency improvements including HVAC system upgrades.</p>

